        }}>{`Fig: Character Constants in C Programming Language `}</figcaption>{`
  `}</figure></p>
    <p>{`Note that the character constant ‘5’ is not the same as the number 5. The last constant is a blank space. Character constants have integer
values known as ASCII values. For example, the statement would print the number 97, the ASCII value of the letter a.`}</p>
    <h2 {...{
      "id": "rules-for-constructing-character-constants"
    }}>{`Rules for Constructing Character Constants`}</h2>
    <ul>
      <li parentName="ul">{`A character constant is a single alphabet, a single digit or a single special symbol enclosed within single inverted commas. Both the inverted
commas should point to the left. For example, ’A’ is a valid character constant whereas ‘A’ is not.`}</li>
      <li parentName="ul">{`The maximum length of a character constant can be 1 character. Ex.: ‘A’ ‘I’, ‘5’ ‘=’.`}</li>
    </ul>
    <h2 {...{
      "id": "string-constants"
    }}>{`String Constants`}</h2>
    <p>{`A string constant, or simply a string, consists of zero or more characters enclosed within double quotation marks. Non-graphic characters may also
be used as part of a character string. Here are some examples:`}</p>
    <pre><code parentName="pre" {...{
        "className": "language-js"
      }}>{`"Madam, I'm Adam"
"Programming in C is fun\\n"
"\\n\\n\\t\\t***** inventory report *****\\n\\n"
`}</code></pre>
    <p>{`The length of a string is the number of characters that form the string. There is no limit on the length of a string.`}</p>
    <h2 {...{
      "id": "backslash-character-constants"
    }}>{`Backslash Character Constants`}</h2>
    <p>{`C supports some special backslash character constants that are used in output functions. For example, the symbol ‘\\n’ stands for newline character.`}</p>
